  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>The monkeys were given a choice. On one side of the cage: water. On the other: alcohol. Vervet monkeys, when offered this arrangement, will drink voluntarily and consistently — not because researchers coaxed them, not because they had no alternative, but because the reward circuitry in a primate brain responds to ethanol the way it was built to respond to anything that floods the nucleus accumbens with dopamine. They want it. Then researchers gave some of them semaglutide. The treated monkeys didn't find alcohol disgusting. They didn't get sick and learn to avoid it. They didn't show signs of distress or withdrawal from the choice itself. They simply stopped caring. The alcohol was there. They just didn't particularly want it anymore.</p>
  <p>That behavioral observation — quiet, undramatic, almost boring in its simplicity — is the most important finding in addiction neuroscience in a decade. Not because it proves semaglutide works in humans. It doesn't prove that. But because of what it implies about the nature of wanting itself. If a metabolic hormone, acting on receptors scattered through the brain's reward circuitry, can extinguish the motivational pull of alcohol without creating aversion, without causing nausea, without substituting one compulsion for another — then the question that follows is not a pharmacological one. It's a conceptual one. What exactly was that wanting? And where did it come from?</p>
  <p>The answer accumulating across a half-dozen large studies, one randomized trial, and twenty years of neuroscience is uncomfortable in the best possible way. It suggests that the craving underlying addiction and the craving underlying hunger are not analogous systems running in parallel. They are the same system. And if that's true, then addiction has been misclassified — not entirely, not simply, but in ways that have shaped how we fund it, treat it, and judge the people who have it.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-data-you-cannot-dismiss" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Data You Cannot Dismiss</h2>
  <p>Start with scale. A 2025 study published in The BMJ examined over 600,000 U.S. veterans with type 2 diabetes and pre-existing substance use disorder. Researchers at Washington University School of Medicine found that GLP-1 receptor agonist use was associated with 50% fewer substance-related deaths, 39% fewer drug overdoses, 26% fewer drug-related hospitalizations, and 25% fewer suicide attempts. These are not marginal signals. These are the kinds of numbers that, in any other therapeutic area, would have triggered emergency regulatory review and fast-track designation.</p>
  <p>The same study found that GLP-1 drugs reduced the risk of developing new substance use disorders: 18% lower risk of alcohol use disorder, 25% lower risk of opioid use disorder, approximately 20% lower risk of cocaine and nicotine dependence. Across every major addictive substance. Simultaneously. From a drug that was designed to lower blood sugar.</p>
  <p>Then there is the Swedish comparison that has been almost entirely absent from mainstream coverage. A nationwide study of 227,000 people with alcohol use disorder, published in JAMA Psychiatry in 2025, found GLP-1 drugs associated with a 36% lower risk of alcohol-related hospitalizations. Naltrexone — the best-performing FDA-approved medication for alcohol use disorder, the drug addiction medicine has relied on for three decades — managed 14%. That is not a marginal improvement over the current standard of care. That is a different category of effect, achieved incidentally, by a drug whose manufacturer has never sought an addiction indication.</p>
  <p>The Lancet Psychiatry added another layer in early 2026. A national cohort study of 95,490 people in Sweden with pre-existing depression or anxiety found semaglutide use associated with a 42% reduced risk of worsening mental illness, a 44% reduced risk of worsening depression, a 38% reduced risk of worsening anxiety, and a 47% reduced risk of worsening substance use disorder — all compared to periods when the same individuals were not using GLP-1 drugs. Lead author Markku Lähteenvuo of the University of Eastern Finland noted that the study's nationwide, inclusive design means "we can be pretty certain that there is an association with using GLP-1s and reduced psychiatric symptoms." Certainty about association is not certainty about causation. But it is not nothing.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"There is no medication that works across addictive substances, let alone all of them. The revelation about GLP-1 medication is that it really works against all major substances — because it is likely acting against the craving itself." — Ziyad Al-Aly, MD, Washington University School of Medicine</p></aside>

<section id="the-mechanism-wanting-vs-liking" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Mechanism: Wanting vs. Liking</h2>
  <p>GLP-1 — glucagon-like peptide-1 — is not primarily a drug. It is a hormone. It is synthesized in the gut in response to food intake, and it is also produced by neurons in the nucleus tractus solitarius (NTS) in the brainstem. It reaches the brain via two routes: activation of vagal afferent fibers projecting upward to the NTS, and direct bloodstream entry at circumventricular organs where the blood-brain barrier is incomplete. The brain, in other words, was already listening to this signal long before anyone put it in a weekly injection.</p>
  <p>GLP-1 receptors are densely expressed in the ventral tegmental area (VTA), the nucleus accumbens (NAc), and the prefrontal cortex — the exact architecture that drives craving for every addictive substance known to medicine. A 2024 paper in Science Advances characterized the mechanism with unusual precision: voluntary cocaine taking decreased plasma GLP-1 levels in rats; chemogenetic activation of GLP-1-producing NTS neurons projecting to the VTA decreased cocaine seeking; GLP-1 receptor agonist pharmacotherapy increased VTA GABA neuron activity and suppressed cocaine-seeking-evoked increases in VTA dopamine neuron activity.</p>
  <p>Translated: in the VTA, GLP-1 receptor activation primarily targets GABA interneurons — the inhibitory cells that regulate dopamine neuron firing. When those interneurons are activated, they dial down the phasic dopamine release in the nucleus accumbens that occurs in response to rewarding stimuli. Food, alcohol, cocaine, nicotine — all of them trigger this dopamine surge. Semaglutide appears to reduce the surge without eliminating the underlying capacity for pleasure.</p>
  <p>This is the distinction that addiction neuroscience has been working toward for decades: wanting versus liking. The terms come from the work of Kent Berridge at the University of Michigan, who demonstrated that the mesolimbic dopamine system primarily encodes motivational salience — the compulsive pull toward a stimulus — rather than hedonic pleasure itself. You can damage the dopamine system and an animal will still show pleasure responses to sugar. But it won't work to get the sugar. The wanting and the liking are dissociable. Semaglutide, based on the animal data and the behavioral observations in humans, appears to suppress wanting. The vervet monkeys could still drink. They just didn't feel the pull.</p>
  <p>For nicotine, the mechanism has an additional wrinkle. A 2025 review in Addiction, co-authored by Nora Volkow, Director of the National Institute on Drug Abuse, identified a distinct pathway: GLP-1 activation of the medial habenular pathway appears to make nicotine's effects aversive, rather than simply reducing motivational salience. The anti-inflammatory effects of GLP-1 receptor agonists via central opioid receptor pathways may also address neuroinflammatory contributions to addiction — a mechanism that has nothing to do with dopamine at all. The drug may be working through multiple routes simultaneously, which would explain why the effect appears consistent across substances with very different pharmacological profiles.</p>
  <p>Ziyad Al-Aly, the Washington University physician who led the 600,000-veteran study, put it plainly: "In addiction medicine, a lot of treatments target just one thing... but there is no medication that works across addictive substances, let alone all of them. The revelation about GLP-1 medication is that it really works against all major substances... because it is likely acting against the craving itself."</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Key Evidence at a Glance</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>BMJ, 2025 (WashU, 600,000+ veterans):</strong> 50% fewer substance-related deaths; 39% fewer overdoses; 25% fewer suicide attempts among people with pre-existing SUD on GLP-1 drugs vs. other diabetes medications.</li>
    <li><strong>JAMA Psychiatry, 2025 (Swedish nationwide, 227,000 AUD patients):</strong> GLP-1 drugs reduced alcohol-related hospitalizations by 36% vs. 14% for naltrexone — the best FDA-approved AUD medication.</li>
    <li><strong>Lancet Psychiatry, 2026 (Sweden, 95,490 patients):</strong> 42% reduced risk of worsening mental illness; 47% reduced risk of worsening substance use disorder during periods of GLP-1 use vs. non-use.</li>
    <li><strong>JAMA Psychiatry RCT, 2025 (48 adults, AUD):</strong> Semaglutide significantly reduced alcohol consumption, peak breath alcohol concentration, drinks per drinking day, and weekly craving — medium-to-large effect sizes. Smokers in the trial also reduced cigarette consumption significantly.</li>
    <li><strong>Nature Communications, 2024 (83,825 patients with obesity):</strong> 50–56% lower risk of AUD incidence and recurrence over 12 months, consistent across gender, age, race, and diabetes status.</li>
    <li><strong>Science Advances, 2024 (preclinical):</strong> GLP-1R activation increases VTA GABA neuron activity and suppresses cocaine-seeking-evoked dopamine surges in rats.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="the-randomized-trial-small-but-real" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Randomized Trial: Small, but Real</h2>
  <p>The observational data, however large, carries an unavoidable problem. People prescribed GLP-1 drugs are not a random sample of the population. They are more likely to be engaged with healthcare, better-resourced, more health-motivated. This healthy-user bias can produce apparent benefits that evaporate under controlled conditions. It has happened before in addiction medicine, repeatedly, with treatments that looked promising in retrospective data and failed in trials.</p>
  <p>The self-controlled cohort design of the Lancet Psychiatry study partially addresses this by comparing individuals to themselves across periods of GLP-1 use and non-use, rather than comparing them to different people. That is a meaningful methodological improvement. It does not eliminate the problem. People may change their behavior in other ways when they start a new medication. They may be more engaged with healthcare generally during treatment periods. The bias does not disappear; it shifts.</p>
  <p>The only study that controls for this properly is the JAMA Psychiatry randomized clinical trial published in 2025, led by Christian Hendershot at the USC Institute for Addiction Science and Klara Klein at UNC School of Medicine. It had 48 participants. Nine weeks. Two lowest clinical doses of semaglutide. Those numbers need to be held in mind alongside the findings, which were striking: low-dose semaglutide significantly reduced laboratory alcohol self-administration with medium-to-large effect sizes, reduced drinks per drinking day, reduced weekly alcohol craving, and reduced heavy drinking days relative to placebo. In the subgroup of smokers, cigarette consumption also fell significantly — a notable signal, since no medication is currently approved for both alcohol reduction and smoking cessation simultaneously.</p>
  <p>Klein's own framing was precise: "These data suggest the potential of semaglutide and similar drugs to fill an unmet need for the treatment of alcohol use disorder. Larger and longer studies in broader populations are needed to fully understand the safety and efficacy." That is not hedging. That is an accurate description of where the evidence stands. The signal is real. The evidence base for clinical application is not yet there.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The STEP trials excluded people with lifetime suicide attempts and active major depressive disorder — meaning the population most likely to need psychiatric benefit is the one least studied."</p></aside>

<section id="the-psychiatric-safety-problem-that-wont-go-away" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Psychiatric Safety Problem That Won't Go Away</h2>
  <p>In 2023, the European Medicines Agency and the FDA both opened formal investigations into semaglutide following pharmacovigilance signals from VigiBase and EudraVigilance — the international and European adverse event reporting systems. The signals flagged increased rates of anxiety (adjusted reporting odds ratio 1.26), depressed mood disorders (aROR 1.70), and suicidality (aROR 1.45). These are not small numbers in pharmacovigilance terms. These are the kinds of signals that have pulled drugs from the market.</p>
  <p>Those investigations remain unresolved.</p>
  <p>Against those signals sits a substantial body of cohort data pointing in the opposite direction. A 2024 Nature Medicine study of 240,618 patients with overweight or obesity found semaglutide associated with significantly lower risk of incident suicidal ideation (HR=0.27) and recurrent suicidal ideation (HR=0.44) compared to non-GLP-1 anti-obesity medications — findings replicated in 1.5 million patients with type 2 diabetes. A 2024 eClinicalMedicine study using propensity-score matched cohorts found semaglutide not associated with increased risk for any of 22 neurological or psychiatric outcomes, including depression, anxiety, suicidality, or substance misuse at 12 months.</p>
  <p>And yet: a large community-based cohort study using post-marketing surveillance data reported a 195% increased risk of major depressive disorder and a 106% increased risk of suicidal behavior among individuals with obesity treated with liraglutide or semaglutide. That finding directly contradicts the positive cohort studies. It has not been retracted. It has not been explained away.</p>
  <p>Gregory Brown of the Penn Center for the Prevention of Suicide offered one framing: "It is certainly possible that individuals with overweight or obesity who take semaglutide may experience depressive symptoms or suicidal ideation or behavior, but the data suggest that persons not taking semaglutide — in the placebo group — are equally likely to experience these conditions." That is a reasonable reading of the randomized trial data. It does not resolve the pharmacovigilance signals, which come from a different population, a different study design, and a different set of confounders.</p>
  <p>The deeper problem is structural. The STEP clinical trials — the pivotal trials that established semaglutide's safety and efficacy for weight management — excluded people with lifetime suicide attempts and active major depressive disorder. This was a reasonable precaution during initial drug development. It is now a significant gap in the evidence base, because the population most likely to benefit from GLP-1 drugs' apparent psychiatric effects is precisely the population that was excluded from the studies that would have characterized those effects. We are trying to understand the psychiatric safety of a drug in a population that was never studied in the trials that generated our safety data.</p>
  <p>There is also a mechanistic concern that deserves more attention than it typically receives. GLP-1 drugs reduce the reward value of food, alcohol, and drugs. They may also reduce the reward value of other things. The general blunting of interest and pleasure that some patients report — sometimes described as food "noise" going quiet, sometimes described as a broader flattening of motivation — raises a question that the current evidence cannot answer: is reduced craving the same thing as reduced hedonic capacity? And if semaglutide is producing anhedonia in some patients, is that being captured in the outcome measures, or is it being misclassified as therapeutic benefit?</p>
</section>

<section id="the-reframe-and-its-limits" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Reframe, and Its Limits</h2>
  <p>The mechanistic story, if it holds, demands a conceptual shift. If GLP-1 receptors in the VTA and nucleus accumbens regulate the dopaminergic response to food, alcohol, cocaine, nicotine, and opioids through the same pathway — if the wanting that drives a binge and the wanting that drives a relapse are expressions of the same underlying signal — then addiction is not merely analogous to a metabolic disorder. It is, in part, a disorder of metabolic reward signaling.</p>
  <p>That reframe is additive, not reductive. The social determinants of addiction are real. Trauma, poverty, housing instability, and social isolation all shape who develops substance use disorders and how severe they become. The psychological dimensions — the learned associations, the coping functions, the identity structures built around use — are real and require real psychological intervention. The environmental dimensions are real. None of that disappears if the mesolimbic dopamine system turns out to be regulated by a gut hormone.</p>
  <p>What changes is the explanatory framework. Addiction has been classified, funded, and treated primarily as a psychiatric and behavioral disorder, with the metabolic and neurological substrate treated as secondary. If GLP-1 receptor signaling is a primary driver of craving — not a parallel system but the same system — then the psychiatric framing is incomplete in the same way that calling type 2 diabetes a "lifestyle disorder" is incomplete. Technically defensible. Mechanistically misleading. And consequential for how resources flow.</p>
  <p>Carolina Haass-Koffler, Associate Professor of Psychiatry at Brown University, framed it this way: "GLP-1s aren't just targeting the brain, like many older medications. They work more holistically, helping the brain and the body." That holism is the point. The brain and the body are not separate systems with separate reward signals. They share one.</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">What We Don't Know Yet</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Craving rebound:</strong> Whether craving returns when GLP-1 drugs are discontinued — and whether that return triggers relapse — is entirely unknown. The drugs may suppress rather than resolve addiction.</li>
    <li><strong>Psychiatric safety in high-risk populations:</strong> The STEP trials excluded people with lifetime suicide attempts and active major depressive disorder. Pharmacovigilance signals for depression and suicidality remain unresolved by the EMA and FDA.</li>
    <li><strong>Optimal dosing for addiction:</strong> The JAMA Psychiatry RCT used the two lowest clinical doses over 9 weeks. Therapeutic dosing, duration, and titration for addiction indications are unknown.</li>
    <li><strong>Human mechanistic confirmation:</strong> Animal models show reduced dopamine release in reward centers, but direct observation in human brains is not yet possible. Species differences in GLP-1R distribution have already been documented.</li>
    <li><strong>Long-term efficacy:</strong> No study has followed addiction outcomes beyond 12 months. Phase 3 trials have not yet reported results.</li>
    <li><strong>Anhedonia vs. craving reduction:</strong> Whether reported reductions in "wanting" reflect genuine craving suppression or broader hedonic blunting remains uncharacterized in the clinical literature.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="the-commercial-silence" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Commercial Silence</h2>
  <p>Novo Nordisk's market capitalization exceeded $500 billion at its 2024 peak, driven almost entirely by semaglutide. The company has pursued obesity, diabetes, cardiovascular disease, kidney disease, metabolic dysfunction-associated steatohepatitis, and Alzheimer's disease as indications. It has not pursued addiction with anything approaching comparable urgency.</p>
  <p>Eli Lilly, with tirzepatide (Mounjaro, Zepbound), has followed a similar trajectory. The addiction signal in the data is not subtle. The 600,000-person VA study, the Swedish nationwide comparison with naltrexone, the Lancet Psychiatry cohort — these are not findings that require specialized expertise to notice. They are findings that require a commercial incentive to act on.</p>
  <p>The addiction population in the United States is large. Approximately 48.7 million Americans met criteria for a substance use disorder in 2022, according to SAMHSA. It is also, critically, often uninsured or publicly insured. Medicaid covers a substantial portion of people with substance use disorders. The reimbursement landscape for a $1,000-per-month injectable medication in a publicly insured, low-income population is not attractive to a company optimizing for shareholder return. That is not an accusation. It is a structural observation about how pharmaceutical development incentives work, and it has direct consequences for which populations get access to which treatments and when.</p>
  <p>Nora Volkow and colleagues, in their 2025 Addiction review, called for "rigorous clinical trials to determine their efficacy, safety and acceptability for treating substance use disorder," while noting the "exciting translational opportunities" the drugs represent. That call is appropriate. The question is who funds those trials if the manufacturers don't, and at what pace the NIH and NIDA can move relative to the scale of the crisis. In 2023, drug overdose deaths in the United States exceeded 107,000. The 50% reduction in substance-related deaths seen in the VA study, applied to that number, is not an abstraction.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The vervet monkeys stopped wanting alcohol. We have 600,000 veterans' worth of data. The science is moving. The question is whether the institutions around it will."</p></aside>

<section id="where-the-evidence-actually-stands" class="reveal">
  <h2>Where the Evidence Actually Stands</h2>
  <p>Semaglutide is not FDA-approved for any addiction indication. Phase 3 trials have not reported. The largest randomized controlled trial in alcohol use disorder had 48 participants over 9 weeks. The mechanistic story in humans, while compelling, is inferred from animal models and receptor distribution data — direct observation of GLP-1-mediated dopamine suppression in living human brains is not yet possible, and species differences in GLP-1 receptor distribution have already been documented between rodents and primates.</p>
  <p>The observational evidence is, by the standards of observational evidence, unusually strong. Multiple large cohorts. Multiple countries. Multiple substances. Consistent effect directions. A self-controlled design that partially addresses healthy-user bias. A comparative effectiveness finding against an active comparator — naltrexone — that is not susceptible to the same confounding as comparisons against no treatment. And one small randomized trial that, despite its size, showed the signal holds under controlled conditions.</p>
  <p>That is not enough to prescribe semaglutide for addiction. It is enough to treat the question with the seriousness it deserves. Twenty years of watching promising addiction treatments fail — rimonabant, vigabatrin, modafinil, a dozen others that looked good in early data — teaches appropriate caution. It does not teach dismissal. The data here are different in kind, not just degree. The effect is appearing across all substances simultaneously. The mechanism is plausible and increasingly characterized. The effect sizes in the comparative effectiveness data are not marginal.</p>
  <p>Roger McIntyre of the University of Toronto has argued that GLP-1 receptor agonists "have potential to transform health outcomes for persons with bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, major depressive disorder and other serious mental illnesses by lengthening healthspan and reducing excess and premature mortality." That is a large claim. It may be right. The evidence does not yet support acting on it at scale. It absolutely supports the Phase 3 trials that would tell us whether it is right.</p>
</section>

